\section*{Problem Analysis}
We have a rapidly rotating, partially-ionised, isothermal cylinder of air that represents a steady typhoon.  
Because of centrifugal separation the heavy positive ions and the light free electrons do not have identical spatial distributions; a net positive charge appears in the outer part of the column and produces a radial electro-static field \(E_{r}(r)\).

An unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) of mass \(m\) and (electric) charge \(q_{0}\) is placed at a fixed height inside the cylinder.  
In steady operation the UAV co–rotates with the gas at the same angular velocity \(\omega\) on a circle of radius \(r_{0}\); the only forces that act in the horizontal plane are the electric force and the usual central (centripetal) force.  
At \(t=0\) the vehicle is given a very small radial velocity \(v_{0}\;(v_{0}\ll\omega r_{0})\).  The motion that follows is a small radial oscillation (an “epicycle’’) superposed on the uniform rotation; in the laboratory frame it appears as a slow precession of the orbit.  We have to find the epicyclic (precession) angular frequency \(\Omega\).

\section*{Solution Strategy}
1.  Obtain the equilibrium spatial densities \(n_{e}(r)\) and \(n_{i}(r)\) of electrons and positive ions from Boltzmann statistics in the rotating frame.  
2.  From these densities determine the net charge density \(\rho_{q}(r)\).  
3.  Use Gauss’ law in cylindrical symmetry to get the radial electric field \(E_{r}(r)\).  
4.  Write the radial equation of motion for the UAV, expand it about the equilibrium radius \(r_{0}\) and keep only terms that are linear in the small displacement.  
5.  From the linearised equation identify the natural angular frequency \(\Omega\) of the small radial oscillations (which equals the observable precession frequency).

Throughout the calculation we use  
\[
k\equiv\frac{\omega^{2}}{2k_{B}T_{0}}\qquad (T_{0}=\text{isothermal temperature})
\]

\section*{Detailed Calculation}

\subsection*{1. Boltzmann distributions in the rotating frame}

The centrifugal potential of a particle of mass \(m\) in the co-rotating frame is  
\[
U(r)=-\frac{1}{2}m\omega^{2}r^{2}.
\]

For an ideal, isothermal gas the number density is  
\[
n(r)=n(0)\,e^{-U(r)/k_{B}T_{0}}
      =n(0)\,\exp\!\!\left(\frac{m\omega^{2}r^{2}}{2k_{B}T_{0}}\right)
      =n(0)\,\exp\!\!\left(mk\,r^{2}\right).
\]

Hence  
\[
n_{e}(r)=n_{0}\,e^{\,m_{e}k r^{2}},\qquad
n_{i}(r)=n_{0}\,e^{\,m_{i}k r^{2}}
\]
with \(n_{0}\equiv n_{e}(0)=n_{i}(0)\) (neutrality at the axis).  
\(m_{e}\) is the electron mass, \(m_{i}  (\simeq m_{\rm tot})\) the ion mass; \(m_{i}\gg m_{e}\).

\subsection*{2. Charge density}

\[
\rho_{q}(r)=e\,[\,n_{i}(r)-n_{e}(r)\,]
            =e\,n_{0}\bigl[e^{\,m_{i}k r^{2}}-e^{\,m_{e}k r^{2}}\bigr].
\tag{1}
\]

\subsection*{3. Radial electric field}

For a long cylinder (\(H\gg R\)) edge effects on the mid-plane may be ignored and Gauss’ law in cylindrical symmetry gives  
\[
\frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dr}\!\bigl(rE_{r}\bigr)=\frac{\rho_{q}(r)}{\varepsilon_{0}}.
\]

Integrating from the axis (where \(E_{r}=0\)) to the general radius \(r\),

\[
E_{r}(r)=\frac{1}{\varepsilon_{0}r}\int_{0}^{r}\rho_{q}(r')\,r'\,dr'
        =\frac{en_{0}}{2\varepsilon_{0}k\,r}
          \Bigl[
             \frac{e^{\,m_{i}k r^{2}}-1}{m_{i}}
            -\frac{e^{\,m_{e}k r^{2}}-1}{m_{e}}
          \Bigr].
\tag{2}
\]

Later we shall also need the derivative  
\[
E_{r}'(r)\equiv\frac{dE_{r}}{dr}.
\]
Differentiating (2) gives (after a few lines of algebra)
\[
E_{r}'(r)=\frac{en_{0}}{\varepsilon_{0}}
          \Bigl[e^{\,m_{i}k r^{2}}-e^{\,m_{e}k r^{2}}\Bigr]
          -\frac{E_{r}(r)}{r}.
\tag{3}
\]

\subsection*{4. Equation of motion of the UAV}

Let the instantaneous cylindrical coordinates of the UAV be \((r,\theta)\).  
Only the central electric force acts horizontally, so in the inertial frame

\[
m\Bigl(\ddot{r}-r\dot{\theta}^{2}\Bigr)=q_{0}E_{r}(r),\qquad
\frac{d}{dt}(m r^{2}\dot{\theta})=0\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
L\equiv m r^{2}\dot{\theta}=\text{constant}.
\tag{4}
\]

\textbf{Steady orbit.}  
For the unperturbed motion (\(r=r_{0},\;\dot{\theta}=\omega\))

\[
q_{0}E_{r}(r_{0})=m\omega^{2}r_{0}.           \tag{5}
\]

\textbf{Effective one–dimensional potential.}  
Define the electro-static potential \(\phi(r)\) by \(E_{r}(r)=-d\phi/dr\).  
With conserved angular momentum \(L=m r_{0}^{2}\omega\) the radial motion can be written as

\[
m\ddot{r}=-\frac{d}{dr}\Bigl[
            {\underbrace{\frac{L^{2}}{2mr^{2}}}_{\text{centrifugal term}}}
            +q_{0}\phi(r)
          \Bigr]
        \equiv -\frac{dU_{\rm eff}}{dr}.
\]

A small displacement \(\delta r\equiv r-r_{0}\) therefore obeys (Taylor expansion)

\[
m\ddot{\delta r}= -U_{\rm eff}''(r_{0})\,\delta r,
\]
so that the square of the epicyclic frequency is

\[
\boxed{\;\Omega^{2}= \frac{1}{m}\,U_{\rm eff}''(r_{0})\;}.          \tag{6}
\]

\subsection*{5. Second derivative of the effective potential}

\paragraph{Centrifugal part.}
With \(L=m r_{0}^{2}\omega\),
\[
\frac{d^{2}}{dr^{2}}\Bigl(\frac{L^{2}}{2mr^{2}}\Bigr)_{r_{0}}
         =\frac{3L^{2}}{m r_{0}^{4}}
         =3\omega^{2}.                                 \tag{7}
\]

\paragraph{Electro-static part.}
Because \(\phi'=-E_{r}\Rightarrow\phi''=-E_{r}'\),
\[
q_{0}\phi''(r_{0}) = -q_{0}E_{r}'(r_{0}).             \tag{8}
\]
Insert (3) evaluated at \(r_{0}\), and use the equilibrium condition (5) to eliminate the unknown density \(n_{0}\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
q_{0}E_{r}'(r_{0})
      &= q_{0}\!\Bigl[\frac{\rho_{q}(r_{0})}{\varepsilon_{0}}-\frac{E_{r}(r_{0})}{r_{0}}\Bigr]    \\
      &= q_{0}\frac{\rho_{q}(r_{0})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
         -\frac{q_{0}}{r_{0}}\Bigl(\frac{m\omega^{2}r_{0}}{q_{0}}\Bigr)
       = q_{0}\frac{\rho_{q}(r_{0})}{\varepsilon_{0}}-m\omega^{2}.
\end{aligned} \tag{9}
\]

\paragraph{Putting everything together.}
Insert (7) and (8) into (6):

\[
\Omega^{2}=3\omega^{2}+\frac{1}{m}\,[\,-q_{0}E_{r}'(r_{0})\,]
          =3\omega^{2}-\frac{q_{0}}{m}\frac{\rho_{q}(r_{0})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
          +\omega^{2}
          =4\omega^{2}-\frac{q_{0}}{m}\frac{\rho_{q}(r_{0})}{\varepsilon_{0}}.
\tag{10}
\]

\subsection*{6. Writing the answer explicitly in terms of \(r_{0}\)}

Using (1) for \(\rho_{q}(r_{0})\),

\[
\Omega^{2}=4\omega^{2}
           -\frac{q_{0}}{m}\,
            \frac{e n_{0}}{\varepsilon_{0}}
            \Bigl[e^{\,m_{i}k r_{0}^{2}}-e^{\,m_{e}k r_{0}^{2}}\Bigr].
\tag{11}
\]

To eliminate the (generally unknown) factor \(n_{0}\) one may combine (11) with the force-balance relation (5) and the explicit field (2).  The result is a very compact, \emph{density–free} form

\[
\boxed{\;
\Omega^{2}= \omega^{2}\,
\Biggl[
     4-\frac{2k r_{0}^{2}
             \bigl(e^{\,m_{i}k r_{0}^{2}}-e^{\,m_{e}k r_{0}^{2}}\bigr)}
            { \dfrac{e^{\,m_{i}k r_{0}^{2}}-1}{m_{i}}
             -\dfrac{e^{\,m_{e}k r_{0}^{2}}-1}{m_{e}} }
\Biggr]
\;}
\tag{12}
\]

where \(k=\dfrac{\omega^{2}}{2k_{B}T_{0}}\).

\medskip
Equation (12) is the exact epicyclic/precession frequency of the UAV expressed solely in terms of the given system parameters and the operating radius \(r_{0}\).  In particular situations one may use limiting forms:  

• For sufficiently large \(r_{0}\) the exponential containing the heavy-ion mass dominates and the bracket approaches a value slightly smaller than \(4\), so \(\Omega\lesssim 2\omega\).  

• For very small \(r_{0}\) (so that \(k r_{0}^{2}\ll1\)) the bracket tends to zero and the oscillation becomes very slow, in agreement with the fact that the charge separation then vanishes.

\section*{Physical interpretation}
The familiar term \(4\omega^{2}\) is the epicyclic frequency squared of a neutral test body in a purely mechanical \(\propto 1/r\) central force field.  
The second term in (10) or (12) is the purely electrical correction.  
If the UAV has the same sign of charge as the net charge density at \(r_{0}\) (\(\rho_{q}>0\) and \(q_{0}>0\)) the electric interaction softens the restoring force and \(\Omega<2\omega\); the opposite sign of \(q_{0}\) stiffens the orbit and \(\Omega>2\omega\).

\bigskip
### Final Answer  

\[
\boxed{ \;
\displaystyle
\Omega^{2}\;=\;
4\omega^{2}\;-\;\frac{q_{0}}{m\,\varepsilon_{0}}\,
en_{0}\Bigl[e^{\,m_{i}k r_{0}^{2}}-e^{\,m_{e}k r_{0}^{2}}\Bigr]
\;=\;
\omega^{2}\!
\Biggl[
     4-\frac{2k r_{0}^{2}\bigl(e^{\,m_{i}k r_{0}^{2}}-e^{\,m_{e}k r_{0}^{2}}\bigr)}
            { \dfrac{e^{\,m_{i}k r_{0}^{2}}-1}{m_{i}}
             -\dfrac{e^{\,m_{e}k r_{0}^{2}}-1}{m_{e}} }
\Biggr]
\;}
\]

(The first equality uses the explicit charge density, the second is a density-free form obtained with the help of the force-balance condition \(q_{0}E_{r}(r_{0})=m\omega^{2}r_{0}\).)
